[[Category:Evolutionary biology]]

'''Genetic divergence''' is the process in which two or more populations of an ancestral species accumulate independent genetic changes ([[mutations]]) through time, often after the populations have become [[Reproductive isolation|reproductively isolated]] for some period of time. In some cases, subpopulations living in ecologically distinct peripheral environments can exhibit genetic divergence from the remainder of a population, especially where the range of a population is very large (see [[parapatric speciation]]). The genetic differences among divergent populations can involve [[silent mutations]] (that have no effect on the [[phenotype]]) or give rise to significant [[Morphology (biology)|morphological]] and/or [[physiology|physiological]] changes. Genetic divergence will always accompany reproductive isolation, either due to novel adaptations via selection and/or due to genetic drift, and is the principal mechanism underlying [[speciation]].<ref name=>{{cite web|url=https://www.boundless.com/biology/textbooks/boundless-biology-textbook/evolution-and-the-origin-of-species-18/evolution-of-genomes-127/gene-duplications-and-divergence-511-13091/ 
|title=Gene Duplications and Divergence|date=8 August 2016|website=Boundless Biology |publisher=Boundless|accessdate=12 January 2017}} Note: this material licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0 for general use, refer link to the website.</ref>

On a molecular genetics level, genetic divergence is due to changes in a small number of [[gene]]s in a species, resulting in [[speciation]].<ref name=Divergence>{{cite journal|last=Palumbi|first=Stephen R.|authorlink=Stephen Palumbi|title=Genetic Divergence, Reproductive Isolation, and Marine Speciation|journal=[[Annual Review of Ecology and Systematics]]|date=1994|volume=25|pages=547–572|jstor=2097324|doi=10.1146/annurev.ecolsys.25.1.547}}</ref> However, researchers argue that it is unlikely that divergence is a result of a significant, single, dominant mutation in a genetic [[locus (genetics)|locus]] because if that were so, the individual with that mutation would have zero [[fitness (biology)|fitness]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Mayr|first1=Ernst|title=Systematics and the Origin of Species|date=1942|publisher=Columbia University Press|location=New York}}</ref> Consequently, they could not reproduce and pass the mutation on to further generations. Hence, it is more likely that divergence, and subsequently [[reproductive isolation]], are the outcomes of multiple small mutations over evolutionary time.<ref name=Divergence />

